05526nmm a2200793Ia 9781501730764DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20182018nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017307647 a10.7591/97815017307642doi  a(DE-B1597)503279  a(OCoLC)1030444126  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHQ799.8.J304a305.253/0917342231 aChatani, Sayaka, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNation-Empire :bIdeology and Rural Youth Mobilization in Japan and Its Colonies /cSayaka Chatani. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (366 p.) :b10 b&w halftones, 3 b&w line drawings, 4 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies of the Weatherhead East Asian Institute, Columbia University0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBy the end of World War II, hundreds of thousands of young men in the Japanese colonies, in particular Taiwan and Korea, had expressed their loyalty to the empire by volunteering to join the army. Why and how did so many colonial youth become passionate supporters of Japanese imperial nationalism? And what happened to these youth after the war? Nation-Empire investigates these questions by examining the long-term mobilization of youth in the rural peripheries of Japan, Taiwan, and Korea. Personal stories and village histories vividly show youth’s ambitions, emotions, and identities generated in the shifting conditions in each locality. At the same time, Sayaka Chatani unveils an intense ideological mobilization built from diverse contexts—the global rise of youth and agrarian ideals, Japan’s strong drive for assimilation and nationalization, and the complex emotions of younger generations in various remote villages.Nation-Empire engages with multiple historical debates. Chatani considers metropole-colony linkages, revealing the core characteristics of the Japanese Empire; discusses youth mobilization, analyzing the Japanese seinendan (village youth associations) as equivalent to the Boy Scouts or the Hitler Youth; and examines society and individual subjectivities under totalitarian rule. Her book highlights the shifting state-society transactions of the twentieth-century world through the lens of the Japanese Empire, inviting readers to contend with a new approach to, and a bold vision of, empire study.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aNationalismzJapanxHistoryy20th century. 0aNationalismzKorea (South)xHistoryy20th century. 0aNationalismzTaiwanxHistoryy20th century. 0aRural youthxPolitical activityzJapanxHistoryy20th century. 0aRural youthxPolitical activityzKorea (South)xHistoryy20th century. 0aRural youthxPolitical activityzTaiwanxHistoryy20th century. 0aYoung menxPolitical activityzJapanxHistoryy20th century. 0aYoung menxPolitical activityzKorea (South)xHistoryy20th century. 0aYoung menxPolitical activityzTaiwanxHistoryy20th century. 4aAsian Studies. 4aChildhood Studies. 4aHistory.  aJapanese Empire, youth mobilization, nationalism, World War II, WWII, Second World War, rural society, Hitlerjugend, Hitler youth, Boy Scouts, Korea, Taiwan, Japan, modern empires, fascist regimes, East Asian International relations.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Packagez978311064982608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060655308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishz978311060425208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018z9783110603255oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PA